    <corollary xml:id="map-of-double-complex-total-qis">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>K^{\bullet,\bullet} \to L^{\bullet,\bullet}</m> be a morphism of double complexes. If the induced maps <m>E_\infty^{p,q}(K) \to E_\infty^{p,q}(L)</m>
          is an isomorphism, then the map <m>\Tot(K^{\bullet,\bullet}) \to \Tot(L^{\bullet,\bullet})</m> is a quasi-isomorphism.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          By <xref ref="prop-spectral-sequence-double-complex"/> (and in particular the naturality), the map
          <m>H^n(\Tot(K^{\bullet,\bullet})) \to H^n(\Tot(L^{\bullet,\bullet}))</m> has the property that it induces isomorphisms on the successive quotients of some filtration.
          By the five lemma, this implies that it is itself an isomorphism.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </corollary>
    <corollary xml:id="map-of-double-complex-first-column-qis">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>K^{\bullet,\bullet}</m> be a double complex in which the single complexes <m>K^{\bullet,q}</m> are acyclic for all <m>q \gt 0</m>. Then the morphism
          <m>\Tot(K^{\bullet,\bullet}) \to K^{\bullet,0}</m> is a quasi-isomorphism.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          Apply <xref ref="map-of-double-complex-total-qis"/> after filling <m>K^{\bullet,0}</m> out to a double complex by adding zeroes.
        </p>
      </proof>
    </corollary>
  </subsection>
  <subsection>
    <title>Totalization in the derived category</title>
    <corollary>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>K^0 \to K^1 \to \cdots</m> be a sequence of morphisms in <m>D(A)</m> for some <m>A \in \Ring</m>, with every two consecutive arrows composing to zero
          (that is, it is a <q>complex consisting of objects of <m>D(A)</m></q>).
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              There exists a way to choose representatives in <m>K(A)</m> so that the terms <m>K^\bullet</m> fit into a double complex.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Given a second such sequence <m>L^\bullet</m> and a morphism <m>K^\bullet \to L^\bullet</m> (i.e., a family of maps forming commuting diagrams in <m>D(A)</m>),
              we can (simultaneously) choose representatives for everything in <m>K(A)</m> so that there exists a morphism of double complexes inducing the given morphism.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The induced map of totalizations is independent of all choices, and is an isomorphism if the original map is an isomorphism.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          The key point is to show that given a double complex <m>K^{\bullet,\bullet}</m> in which the second argument is bounded in the range <m>0,\dots,n</m>
          and a map from <m>K^{\bullet,n} \to L^\bullet</m> in <m>D(A)</m>, we can change <m>L^\bullet</m> to another representative in <m>D(A)</m>
          <em>without changing <m>K^{\bullet,\bullet}</m></em> so that we can add a new column to the complex. We leave the details of this to the reader.
          (Once everything else is done, the very last point follows from <xref ref="map-of-double-complex-total-qis"/>.)
        </p>
      </proof>
    </corollary>
  </subsection>
</section>